[[Image:lamen angelic english.jpg|thumb|right|John Dee's [[Enochian magic|Heptarchic]] Lamen]] A '''''lamen''''' (Latin, meaning "plate") is a magical [[pendant]] or breastplate worn around the neck so that it hangs upon the breast over the heart.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/960711730|title=Circles of power : an introduction to Hermetic magic|last=Greer|first=John Michael|publisher=|year=|isbn=9781904658856|edition= Third |location=London|pages=180–181|oclc=960711730}}</ref> Its uses vary but, most commonly, the term refers to a symbol of authority and a focus of magical energies.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/21907195|title=The Golden Dawn : a complete course in practical ceremonial magic : the original account of the teachings, rites, and ceremonies of the Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn (Stella Matutina)|last=Israel.|first=Regardie,|date=1989|publisher=Llewellyn Publications|others=Monnastre, Cris, 1946-, Weschcke, Carl Llewellyn, 1930-2015.|isbn=0875426638|edition= 6th, rev. and enl.|location=St. Paul, Minn., U.S.A.|oclc=21907195}}</ref> [[Aleister Crowley]] described the lamen as "a sort of [[Coat of Arms]]. It expresses the character and powers of the wearer."<ref name="crowley">Crowley, Aleister, [http://hermetic.com/crowley/magick-without-tears/mwt_20.html "Chapter XX: Talismans: The Lamen: The Pantacle"],''Magick Without Tears'', Phoenix, AZ: Falcon Press, 1973.</ref> Crowley and DuQuette have proposed that the magical lamen might be a modern adaptation of the [[priestly breastplate]] of the ancient Hebrews.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1014451350|title=MAGICK.|last=ALEISTER.|first=CROWLEY,|date=2017|publisher=LULU COM|year=|isbn=9781387338436|location=[S.l.]|pages=66|oclc=1014451350}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/772197864|title=Enochian vision magick : an introduction and practical guide to the magick of Dr. John Dee and Edward Kelley|last=1948-|first=DuQuette, Lon Milo,|date=2008|publisher=WeiserBooks|year=|isbn=9781609250133|location=San Francisco, CA|pages=37|oclc=772197864}}</ref>
The magician may wear a ''lamen'' as a representation of his personal relation to his godhead or the universal forces of balance and enlightenment.<ref name=":0" />
Within group ceremony, ''lamens'' are frequently worn as symbols of particular offices or roles within the ritual work.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/25632048|title=Secrets of a Golden Dawn temple : the alchemy and crafting of magickal implements|last=1936-|first=Cicero, Chic,|date=1992|publisher=Llewellyn Publications|others=Cicero, Sandra Tabatha, 1959-|isbn=0875421504|edition= 1st|location=St. Paul, Minn., U.S.A.|oclc=25632048}}</ref> Many [[magical order]]s also use a particular ''lamen'' design to show membership and align energies of individual members with the group dynamic.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" />
[[File:Rose Cross Lamen.svg|thumb|[[Rose Cross]] ''Lamen'' as used by the Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn]] Various [[Magical organization|Magical Orders]] use ''lamens'' in one or more of these ways, including [[Ordo Templi Orientis]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zeroequalstwo.net/vintage-thelema-lodge-account-of-the-lamen-of-oto/|title=Vintage Thelema Lodge Account of the Lamen of OTO – Zero Equals Two!|website=zeroequalstwo.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref> and [[Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn]].<ref name=":1" />
''Lamens'' may also be used by magicians to evoke certain spirits of the [[Key of Solomon|Key(s) of Solomon]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/42863281|title=The key of Solomon the King (Clavicula Salomonis)|date=2000|publisher=Samuel Weiser|others=Solomon, King of Israel,, Mathers, S. L. MacGregor (Samuel Liddell MacGregor), 1854-1918,|isbn=9780877289319|location=York Beach, Me.|oclc=42863281}}</ref> Specialized ''lamens'' are also used in the workings described in [[The Book of Abramelin]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1990985|title=The book of the sacred magic of Abramelin the mage, as delivered by Abraham the Jew unto his son Lamech, A.D. 1458|last=century.|first=Abraham ben Simeon, of Worms, active 15th|date=1975|publisher=Dover Publications|others=Mathers, S. L. MacGregor (Samuel Liddell MacGregor), 1854-1918.|isbn=0486232115|location=New York|oclc=1990985}}</ref>
