'''Munib Shahid''' (1908-1973) was Chairman of Hematology and Oncology at the Faculty of Medicine of the [[American University of Beirut]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= Mishalany |first= H |last2= |first2= |date= April 1973 |title= Professor Munib Shahid, 1908-1973 |journal= Le Journal Medical Libanais, The Lebanese Medical Journal | volume= 26 |issue= 4 |page= 323 |doi= }}</ref><ref name="Nassar">{{cite book |last= Nassar |first= Mounir (Munir) |date= May 7, 2014 |title= Clinical Medicine Research History at the American University of Beirut, Faculty of Medicine 1920-1974 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=RFWRAwAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&dq=Clinical+Medicine+Research+History+at+the+American+University+of+Beirut,+Faculty+of+Medicine+1920-1974#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= Bloomington, Indiana |publisher= WestBow Press |pages= 61-62 |isbn= 978-1-4908-3279-1}}</ref> He built the hematology laboratory at the Faculty of Medicine, a development that increased research output significantly.<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date= Summer 2007 |title= Faculty of Medicine and Medical Center: Deep Roots, Endless Skies |url= http://staff.aub.edu.lb/~webmgate/summer2007/article6.htm |journal= MainGate |volume= V |issue= 4 |pages= |doi= |access-date= November 3, 2016 }}</ref> The Dr. Munib Shahid Award is presented annually at the American University of Beirut to the fourth year medical student demonstrating the best performance in internal medicine and a mature character.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://docplayer.net/14778430-University-prizes-and-awards.html |title= University Prizes and Awards |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= November 3, 2016| page = 5 |quote=}}</ref>
==Background and Family== Munib Shahid was born in 1908 in [[Acre, Palestine]] to a prominent [[Bahá'u'lláh's family|Bahá'í lineage]]. His parents were Mírzá Jalal, an [[Afnán]], and Rúḥá Khánum. His paternal grandfather was Mírzá Muhammad-Hasan, titled "[[Núrayn-i-Nayyirayn|King of the Martyrs]]," while his maternal grandparents were [[`Abdu'l-Bahá]], the successor to the [[Bahá'í]] founder-prophet [[Bahá'u'lláh]], and [[Munirih Khánum]]. As a prominent member of the [[Bahá'í Faith]], Munib Shahid worked diligently to promote his faith. As a medical student at the American University of Beirut, his friends included such prominent Bahá'ís as future [[Hand of the Cause of God]] [[Abu'l-Qásim Faizi]]. After graduating from medical school, Munib Shahid would continue to promote the Bahá'í Faith, and in 1937 he visited Bahá'í communities in Europe.<ref>{{cite book |last= Effendi |first= Shoghi | authorlink = Shoghi Effendi |date= 1980 |title= The Baha'i World 1936-1938 (Volume VII) |url= https://bahai.works/Bah%C3%A1%E2%80%99%C3%AD_World/Volume_7/Part_1/Survey_of_Current_Bah%C3%A1%E2%80%99%C3%AD_Activities_in_the_East_and_West#pg110 |location= |publisher= Baha'i Publishing Trust |page= 110 |isbn=}}</ref>
In 1944, Munib Shahid married [[Serene Husseini Shahid|Serene Husseini]], the daughter of [[Jamal al-Husayni]]. [[Shoghi Effendi]], the [[Guardian (Bahá'í Faith)|Guardian]] of the Bahá'í Faith and Munib's cousin through `Abdu'l-Bahá's eldest daughter Ḍíyá'íyyih Khánum, labeled this marriage a "treacherous act" and excommunicated Munib Shahid as a [[Covenant-breaker]]. Shoghi Effendi sent the following cable to the Bahá'í world in November 1944:
{{quote|Monib Shahid, grandson of both `Abdu'l-Bahá and the [[Núrayn-i-Nayyirayn|King of Martyrs]], married according to the Moslem rites the daughter of a political exile who is [[Jamal al-Husayni|nephew]] of the [[Grand Mufti of Jerusalem]]. This treacherous act of alliance with enemies of the Faith merits condemnation of entire Bahá'í world."<ref>{{cite news | date=December 1944| title=Messages from the Guardian |url=https://bahai.works/Baha%27i_News/Issue_172 |newspaper=Bahá'í News|issue=172 |access-date=May 8, 2016 }}</ref> (''[[Bahá'í News]]'', No. 172)}}
Munib and Serene Husseini continued to live in Beirut, where he pursued his academic career, and she promoted cottage industries among [[Palestinian refugees]]. Serene Shahid wrote a critically acclaimed autobiography of her childhood, titled, ''Jerusalem Memories.''<ref>{{cite book |last= Shahid |first= Serene|authorlink= Serene Husseini Shahid |date= 1999 |title= Jerusalem Memories |url= http://www.palestine-studies.org/sites/default/files/jq-articles/37-jerusalem_childhood_2.pdf |location= Beirut, Lebanon |publisher= Naufal |page= |isbn=}}</ref> The couple had three daughters, including [[Leila Shahid]].
Munib Shahid died in 1973.{{cn|date=August 2017}}
==Selected publications== Among Shahid's publications were:<ref name="Nassar">{{cite book |last= Nassar |first= Mounir (Munir) |date= May 7, 2014 |title= Clinical Medicine Research History at the American University of Beirut, Faculty of Medicine 1920-1974 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=RFWRAwAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&dq=Clinical+Medicine+Research+History+at+the+American+University+of+Beirut,+Faculty+of+Medicine+1920-1974#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= Bloomington, Indiana |publisher= WestBow Press |pages= 61-62 |isbn= 978-1-4908-3279-1}}</ref> * (with H.A. Yenikomshian) "Typhoid Fever in Inocculated and Noninocculated Persons," ''Journe'es Medicales Libanais de Beyrouth'' (May 1938) 241-247. * "The Use of Nitrogen Mustard in Neoplastic Diseases of the Bone Marrow," ''Rev. Med. Liban.'' I (1961?): 45-51. * (with E. Stephan) "Perarterite noueuse-Maladie de Kussmaul." ''Rev. Med. Moy. Or.'' VI (1949): 295-303. * "ACTH et cortisone en hematologie." ''Rev. Med. Moy. Or.'' XI (1954): 279-291. * "Quelques considerations sur le favisme au Liban." ''Rev. Med. Moy. Or.'' (1960): 83-86. * (with N.A. Abu-Haydar) "Sickle Cell Disease in Lebanon and Syria." ''Acta Haemat., Basel'' XXVII (1962):268-273. * (with G.I. Abu-Haydar and N.A. Abu-Haydar) "Thalassemia Hemoglobin E. Disease. A Case Report from Quatar." ''Persian Gulf, Man.,'' CLV (1963):129. * "Hemoglobinopathies in Lebanon and Arab Countries." ''Proc. IXth Congr. European Soc. Haemat.,'' II (1963):496-500. * "Iron Absorption in Thalassemia." ''Abstr. IXth Congr. Int. Soc. Haemat.'' (Stockholm, 1964.)
