{{short description|10th-century Chinese line drawing}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = Sogdian-Zoroastrian Deities, Tunhwang.jpg | painting_alignment = right | image_size = | title = Sogdian Deities | other_language_1=[[Traditional Chinese characters|Chinese]] | other_title_1={{lang|zh-Hant|粟特神祇白畫|italic=no}} | other_language_2=[[French language|French]] | other_title_2={{lang|fr|Deux divinités féminines}} | artist = Unknown | year = 10th century | type = Ink with light colouring on paper | height_metric = 30.5 | width_metric = 37.8 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | city = [[Paris]] | museum = [[Bibliothèque nationale de France]] }}
'''''Sogdian Deities''''',<ref name=Uygur-Tunhwang>{{cite journal |last=Russell-Smith |first=Lilla Bikfalvy |date=2003 |title=Wives and Patrons: Uygur Political and Artistic Influence in Tenth-century Dunhuang |url=https://archive.org/stream/2003AAAH56401-428WivesPatrons/2003%20AAAH%2056%20401%E2%80%93428%20Wives%20%26%20Patrons#page/n10/mode/1up |journal=Acta Orientalia Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae |volume=56 |issue=2/4 |page=411 |doi= |access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref> or '''''Sogdian Daēnās'''''<ref name=Zoroastrian-Flame>{{cite book |editor-last1=Williams |editor-first1=Alan |editor-last2=Stewart |editor-first2=Sarah |editor-last3=Hintze |editor-first3=Almut |editor-link3=Almut Hintze |date=2016 |title=The Zoroastrian Flame: Exploring Religion, History and Tradition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rp2LDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT102&lpg=PT102&dq=The+Sogdian+Da%C4%93n%C4%81s&source=bl&ots=JpU5Dk0g65&sig=wP8XCDMgSo45hb2GW6TuOAMFAkA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiVpvDL6ObeAhWoxYUKHeFQAq4Q6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=The%20Sogdian%20Da%C4%93n%C4%81s&f=false |location=London |publisher=I.B.Tauris |page= |isbn=9780857728869}}</ref> ({{lang-fr|'''Deux divinités féminines'''}}; {{lang-zh|t=粟特神祇白畫}}) is a 10th-century [[Line art|line drawing]] discovered by the French Orientalist [[Paul Pelliot]] at the [[Mogao Caves]]. It was painted during the late [[Tang dynasty]] and the [[Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period]], and is probably associated with the [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] cult of the [[Sogdia]]n people. The historian {{ill|Zhang Guangda|zh|張廣達}}, who is a member of the [[Academia Sinica]] of [[Taiwan]], recognised this "paper image" as one of the "pieces of paper depicting [[Mazdean]] deities for the {{transl|zh|saixian}} celebration".{{refn|group=note|The {{transl|zh|saixian}} or {{transl|zh|sai-hsien}} (in Chinese: {{lang|zh-Hant|賽祆}}) is a form of a folk cult,<ref>{{cite book |last=Rong |first=Xinjiang |translator-last=Galambos |translator-first=Imre |translator-link=Imre Galambos |date=2013 |title=Eighteen Lectures on Dunhuang |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HvIa9sere_8C&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=the+saixian+cult&source=bl&ots=N2KsgzbSzx&sig=nr_dLn_rlwnpdW8qmgafx9lERZk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiIg9ap9ObeAhUJWBoKHX0NB-YQ6AEwAXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=the%20saixian%20cult&f=false |location=Leiden |publisher=Brill Publishers |page=73 |isbn=9789004252332}}</ref> a Zoroastrian festival celebrated by the Sogdians in the 9th to 10th-century [[Tunhwang]]. The term {{transl|zh|Xianjiao}} or {{transl|zh|Hsien-chiao}} ({{lang|zh-Hant|祆敎}}) means ''Zoroastrianism''.}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Drège |first=Jean-Pierre |date=2007 |title=Études de Dunhuang et Turfan |trans-title=Dunhuang and Turfan Studies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=guIVdC2y9PcC&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64&dq=Deux+divinit%C3%A9s+f%C3%A9minines+monochrome&source=bl&ots=DIS_cZGGqJ&sig=GbRGMhzgJbl5OJQvBOLfvJLQxhg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLgv6KjLncAhUGnRoKHUl7A34Q6AEIQzAI#v=onepage&q=Deux%20divinit%C3%A9s%20f%C3%A9minines%20monochrome&f=false |language=fr |location=Geneva |publisher=Librairie Droz |page=64 |isbn=978-2-600-01132-7 |quote=Zhang Guangda voit dans les dépenses de « papier à image » en rapport avec le culte mazdéen des feuilles « de papier pour peindre les divinités mazdéennes destinées au {{transl|zh|saixian}} ».}}</ref> The drawing is preserved in the [[Bibliothèque nationale de France]] in Paris.
== Description == This sketch, painted on paper in black ink with light colouring, depicts two ladies sitting opposite each another, their heads being encircled by [[Halo (religious iconography)|nimbi]]. Both are represented holding various attributes: the lady on the left, who sits on a rectangular throne supported by a row of lotus petals, holds a foliated cup and a tray with a dog seated on it. The one on the right is seated on a dog or wolf, and has four arms, the upper two supporting the sun and moon discs, the lower two arms holding a scorpion and a snake. They wear a characteristic hairstyle, surmounted by a water-drop-shaped or peach-shaped headdresses that are probably made of metal.<ref name=Uygur-Tunhwang />
== Analysis == [[File:Dunhuang mogao mural cave 409.jpg|thumb|190px|The [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] ladies have the same hairstyle. 10th-century fresco at the [[Mogao Caves]].]] The drawing had been published in [[Jao Tsung-I]]'s ''The Line Drawing of Dunhuang'' in 1978, but has only attracted the interest of researchers since it was displayed in the [[Serindia|Sérinde]] exhibition in 1995.<ref name=Uygur-Tunhwang />
The peach-shaped headdress resembles the hairstyle of the [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] princess. The dress of the lady on the left, at least, does not seem to correspond to the Chinese fashion at the time, and both representing the expression of foreign beliefs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cc8830k/cd0e17692 |title=Cote : Pelliot chinois 4518 (24) – Deux divinités féminines |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr |language=fr |access-date=22 November 2018 |quote=Elle ressemble à la coiffure de la princesse ouïghoure.}}</ref>
According to Jiang Boqin ({{lang|zh-Hant|姜伯勤}})—a professor at [[Sun Yat-sen University]]—it is a piece of Zoroastrian art, and the four-armed deity is a Sogdian goddess worshipped in their Zoroastrian cult, whose name is {{lang|ae-Latn|Nanâ|italic=no}}, or Nanaia,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nansha.schina.ust.hk/Article_DB/sites/default/files/pubs/Jour-03.2.B02.pdf |title=姜伯勤《中國祆教藝術史》書評 |last=Wu |first=Yu |date=2004 |website=schina.ust.hk |language=zh-Hant |access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref> the goddess originated from [[Mesopotamia]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Gorshenina |first1=Svetlana |author-link1=Svetlana Gorshenina |last2=Rapin |first2=Claude |date=2001 |title=De Kaboul à Samarcande : Les archéologues en Asie centrale |series=Collection "[[Découvertes Gallimard]]" |volume=411 |location=Paris |publisher=Éditions Gallimard |page=107 |chapter=Chapitre 5 : Des Kouchans à l'Islam – La peinture sogdienne |language=fr |isbn=978-2-070-76166-1 |quote=Dans la peinture on rencontre ainsi des versions du ''Panchatantra'', l'histoire de la déesse Nana originaire de Mésopotamie.}}</ref> [[Frantz Grenet]]—a French specialist on Sogdiana and Zoroastrianism—and the historian [[Zhang Guangda]] argue that the lady on the left representing [[Daēnā]], the good according to Zoroastrian vision; the other one represents [[Daēva]], the bad.<ref name=Zoroastrian-Flame /> Jiang Boqin agrees with Grenet and Zhang that the deity on the left being Daēnā, but he determined the one on the right is the goddess Nanâ.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://big5.xjass.cn/ls/content/2013-11/22/content_304687.htm |title=敦煌與中外關係史研究三十年 |last=Wang |first=Xusong |date=2013 |website=xjass.cn |language=zh-Hant |access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref>
