{{Contains Indic text}}
'''Utkatasana''' ({{IPAc-en|uː|t|k|ɑː|ˈ|t|ɑː|s|ɑː|n|ɑː}} {{respell|oot|kah|TAH|sah|nah}}<ref name="The complete idiot's guide to yoga">{{cite book |last1=Budilovsky |first1=Joan |last2=Adamson |first2=Eve |title=The complete idiot's guide to yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b5pE8-Oyly0C |accessdate=11 April 2011 |edition=2 |year=2000 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-02-863970-3 |page=149}}</ref>{{Dubious|date=March 2012}}; {{lang-sa|उत्कटासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''Utkaṭāsana''), '''Chair Pose''',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.yogajournal.com/poses/493 | title = Yoga Journal - Chair Pose | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> '''Fierce Pose''',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.yogaartandscience.com/poses/Standing%20Poses/utkat/utkat.html | title = Utkatasana | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref><ref name="Hirschl2010">{{cite book |last=Hirschl |first=Meta Chaya |title=Vital Yoga: A Sourcebook for Students and Teachers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MdweviFuTy0C&pg=PA129 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |year=2010 |publisher=Prajna Publishing |isbn=978-0-9823055-0-8 |page=129}}</ref> '''Hazardous Pose''',<ref name="Pranavananda1997">{{cite book |author=Yogi Pranavananda |title=Pure Yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fPPBXyMM_LwC&pg=PA63 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=1 January 1997 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ. |isbn=978-81-208-1508-7 |page=63}}</ref> '''Lightning Bolt Pose''',<ref name="The complete idiot's guide to yoga"/> '''Wild Pose'''<ref name="Utkatasana - AshtangaYoga.info">{{cite web | url = http://www.ashtangayoga.info/practice/asana-vinyasa-series/primary-series-yoga-chikitsa/item/utkatasana/ | title = Utkatasana - AshtangaYoga.info | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> in which the knees are hips-width apart, the knees are bent, hips are back, chest is forward, and arms are above head, in line with the ears <ref>http://www.yogabasics.com/asana/chair/</ref>. The other possible etymology is ut+kati which means 'high waist' as suggested by madhav kayastha.
==Etymology== The name comes from the Sanskrit words ''utkata'' (उत्कट, utkaṭa) meaning "wild, frightening, above the usual, intense, gigantic, furious, or heavy",<ref name="Utkatasana - AshtangaYoga.info"/> and ''asana'' (आसन) meaning "posture" or "seat".<ref name="Sinha1996">{{cite book|last=Sinha|first=S.C.|title=Dictionary of Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zzRvh1fRzEC&pg=PA18|accessdate=9 April 2011|date=1 June 1996|publisher=Anmol Publications PVT. LTD.|isbn=978-81-7041-293-9|page=18}}</ref>
==Variations== Variations include:<ref name="Inc.2004">{{cite book |author=Active Interest Media, Inc. |title=Yoga Journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4OkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA73 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=2004-09 - 2004-10 |publisher=Active Interest Media, Inc. |page=73 |issn=0191-0965}}</ref>
